[![Elephants in front of the Royal Palace](https://globalvoicesonline.org/wp-
content/uploads/2015/07/elephants-
cambodia.jpg)](http://anom.archivesnationales.culture.gouv.fr/sdx/ulysse/ecran?id=FR%20CAOM%2030Fi127/35&relation=photos/DAFANCAOM01_30FI127N035_P&qid=sdx_q8&p=5)

Elephants in front of the Royal Palace

The French Archives’ nationales de outré-mer (Centre for Overseas Archives)
has digitized thousands of photos in its collection, including historic
documents related to French Indochina. We searched the digital library and
found [rare
images](http://anom.archivesnationales.culture.gouv.fr/sdx/ulysse/resultats?bqid=sommaire&type=Photographie&mode=list&Submit=Afficher)
of Cambodia in the 1920s and 1930s.

Cambodia became a French protectorate in 1867 and gained its independence in
1953. The photos [reveal](https://leminhkhai.wordpress.com/2015/06/29/visions-
of-modernity-in-french-indochina/) everyday life in Cambodia during French
colonial rule. They are significant resources for those who are interested in
learning more not only about Cambodia’s colonial past but also its rich
culture.

Some of the rural scenes are familiar but many of the urban landscapes
featured in the digital archives are already gone, evidence of the rapid
evolution of Phnom Penh and other cities of Cambodia.

Below are some of the photos that highlight the charm of old Cambodia, which
was once known as Pearl of Asia:

